                    <div class="section" id="what_is_bias">
                        <div class="section-header"><h3>WHAT IS UNCONSCIOUS BIAS?</h3></div>
                        <div class="section-content"><div class="section-content-wrapper"><div class="key-definition-box"><h4>DEFINITION</h4><div><p><b>Unconscious bias</b> refers to the automatic judgements and assumptions we make about people without realising it.</p><p>These biases operate outside our conscious awareness – we do not choose to have them, and we are often unaware when they influence our thinking.</p></div></div></div><div class="section-content-wrapper"><div class="text-content-render"><p><b>Unconscious bias explained simply:</b></p><p>Our brains process an enormous amount of information every second. To cope, our brains create <b>mental shortcuts</b> – quick ways of categorising and making sense of the world around us.</p><p>These shortcuts help us make fast decisions. But they can also lead us to make snap judgements about people based on:</p><ul><li>Their appearance</li><li>Their name</li><li>Their accent or way of speaking</li><li>Their age, gender, or background</li><li>Stereotypes we have absorbed from society</li></ul></div></div><div class="section-content-wrapper"><div class="key-definition-box"><h4>KEY CHARACTERISTICS OF UNCONSCIOUS BIAS</h4><div><p><b>1. Automatic Mental Shortcuts</b></p><p>Unconscious biases are not deliberate choices. They happen automatically, without our conscious input. Our brains are constantly taking shortcuts to process information quickly – and these shortcuts can lead to biased thinking.</p><p><b>2. Often Unintentional</b></p><p>Most people who act on their biases do not intend to discriminate or be unfair. They genuinely believe they are being objective. This is what makes unconscious bias so challenging – we cannot see our own blind spots without actively looking for them.</p><p><b>3. Influenced by Our Experiences</b></p><p>Our biases are shaped by our upbringing, culture, media, personal experiences, and the environments we have lived and worked in. They reflect patterns we have absorbed over a lifetime.</p><p><b>4. Can Conflict with Our Values</b></p><p>You might genuinely value fairness and equality, yet still have unconscious biases that lead you to favour certain people over others. This disconnect between our conscious values and unconscious biases is normal – and recognising it is the first step to addressing it.</p></div></div></div><div class="section-content-wrapper"><div class="text-content-render"><p><b>An everyday example:</b></p><p>Imagine you receive two identical CVs for a job. The only difference is the name at the top – one has a traditionally British name, the other has an unfamiliar foreign name.</p><p>Research shows that many people will unconsciously rate the CV with the familiar name more favourably – even when they genuinely believe they are being objective.</p><p>This is unconscious bias in action. The person reviewing the CVs is not trying to be unfair – their brain is simply taking a shortcut based on familiarity.</p></div></div></div>
                        <div class="navigation-buttons">
