                    <div class="section" id="common_biases">
                        <div class="section-header"><h3>COMMON WORKPLACE BIASES</h3></div>
                        <div class="section-content"><div class="section-content-wrapper"><div class="key-definition-box"><h4>FIVE BIASES EVERY LEADER SHOULD KNOW</h4><div><p>While there are many types of unconscious bias, the following five are particularly common in workplace settings. Understanding these will help you recognise when they might be influencing your decisions.</p></div></div></div>

<div class="section-content-wrapper"><div class="bias-card"><h5>1. AFFINITY BIAS</h5><p class="definition"><b>What it is:</b> The tendency to favour people who are similar to us – who share our background, interests, experiences, or characteristics.</p><div class="example"><p class="example-label">Workplace Example:</p><p>A manager consistently gives high-profile projects to team members who went to similar universities, enjoy the same hobbies, or share their communication style – without realising they are overlooking equally capable team members who are "different" from them.</p></div></div></div>

<div class="section-content-wrapper"><div class="bias-card"><h5>2. CONFIRMATION BIAS</h5><p class="definition"><b>What it is:</b> The tendency to look for, notice, and remember information that confirms what we already believe – while ignoring or dismissing information that contradicts it.</p><div class="example"><p class="example-label">Workplace Example:</p><p>A team leader believes a particular employee is "not management material." When reviewing their performance, the leader focuses on minor mistakes while overlooking strong achievements – unconsciously gathering evidence that supports their existing opinion.</p></div></div></div>

<div class="section-content-wrapper"><div class="bias-card"><h5>3. GENDER BIAS</h5><p class="definition"><b>What it is:</b> Unconscious assumptions about what people can or should do based on their gender. This can affect expectations, opportunities, and how behaviour is interpreted.</p><div class="example"><p class="example-label">Workplace Example:</p><p>When a woman speaks assertively in a meeting, she might be labelled "aggressive" or "difficult." When a man displays the same behaviour, he is seen as "confident" and "leadership material." The same behaviour is judged differently based on gender.</p></div></div></div>

<div class="section-content-wrapper"><div class="bias-card"><h5>4. AGE BIAS (AGEISM)</h5><p class="definition"><b>What it is:</b> Making assumptions about people based on their age – whether they are "too young" to be capable or "too old" to learn new things.</p><div class="example"><p class="example-label">Workplace Example:</p><p>A younger employee is passed over for a client-facing role because someone assumes they "lack experience," without actually assessing their skills. Alternatively, an older employee is not considered for a digital project because of assumptions that they "won't understand the technology."</p></div></div></div>

<div class="section-content-wrapper"><div class="bias-card"><h5>5. THE HALO EFFECT</h5><p class="definition"><b>What it is:</b> Allowing one positive characteristic to influence our overall judgement of a person, creating a "halo" that colours everything else we see.</p><div class="example"><p class="example-label">Workplace Example:</p><p>An employee gives an excellent presentation. From that point on, their manager assumes they must be great at everything – overlooking performance issues in other areas. The "halo" from one success blinds the manager to a more balanced view of the employee's strengths and development areas.</p></div></div></div>

<div class="section-content-wrapper"><div class="text-content-render"><p><b>Remember:</b></p><p>These biases are not character flaws – they are patterns in how human brains work. The first step to countering them is simply being aware that they exist and watching for them in your own thinking.</p></div></div></div>
                        <div class="navigation-buttons">
                            <button class="nav-btn" onclick="previousSection()">Previous</button>
