                    <div class="section" id="bias_impact">
                        <div class="section-header"><h3>HOW BIAS CAN AFFECT WORKPLACE DECISIONS</h3></div>
                        <div class="section-content"><div class="section-content-wrapper"><div class="key-definition-box"><h4>THE REAL-WORLD IMPACT OF BIAS</h4><div><p>Unconscious bias does not stay in our heads – it shapes the decisions we make every day. In the workplace, these biased decisions can have significant consequences for individuals, teams, and organisations.</p></div></div></div>

<div class="section-content-wrapper"><div class="interactive-activity-wrapper"><div class="accordion-container"><div class="accordion-item"><div class="accordion-header">Recruitment and Hiring</div><div class="accordion-content"><p><b>How bias shows up:</b></p><ul><li>Favouring candidates with familiar-sounding names or backgrounds</li><li>Making quick judgements based on appearance in the first few seconds of an interview</li><li>Asking different questions to different candidates based on assumptions</li><li>Hiring people who "fit in" rather than those who bring diverse perspectives</li></ul><p><b>The impact:</b></p><p>Qualified candidates are overlooked. Teams become homogeneous, missing out on diverse thinking. The same "type" of person keeps getting hired, reinforcing existing patterns.</p></div></div><div class="accordion-item"><div class="accordion-header">Performance Reviews and Feedback</div><div class="accordion-content"><p><b>How bias shows up:</b></p><ul><li>Rating people we like more favourably (affinity bias)</li><li>Focusing on evidence that confirms our existing views (confirmation bias)</li><li>Using vague language like "cultural fit" that can mask bias</li><li>Applying different standards to different groups (e.g., judging assertiveness differently by gender)</li></ul><p><b>The impact:</b></p><p>Some employees receive less constructive feedback and fewer development opportunities. Performance ratings become unreliable and unfair. Talented people become demotivated or leave.</p></div></div><div class="accordion-item"><div class="accordion-header">Promotions and Opportunities</div><div class="accordion-content"><p><b>How bias shows up:</b></p><ul><li>Promoting people who remind us of ourselves or past successful leaders</li><li>Assuming certain people "wouldn't want" stretch assignments without asking them</li><li>Overlooking achievements from people we have already labelled as "not leadership material"</li><li>Sponsoring and mentoring people we naturally connect with more</li></ul><p><b>The impact:</b></p><p>Leadership teams lack diversity. Capable people are stuck in roles below their potential. The same groups keep advancing while others are left behind.</p></div></div><div class="accordion-item"><div class="accordion-header">Daily Team Interactions</div><div class="accordion-content"><p><b>How bias shows up:</b></p><ul><li>Interrupting some team members more than others</li><li>Crediting ideas to certain people while ignoring the same ideas from others</li><li>Making assumptions about who should take notes, organise social events, or do "office housework"</li><li>Including some people in informal conversations while excluding others</li></ul><p><b>The impact:</b></p><p>Some team members feel invisible or undervalued. Trust and psychological safety decrease. The team does not get the benefit of everyone's contributions.</p></div></div></div></div></div>

<div class="section-content-wrapper"><div class="key-definition-box"><h4>THE CUMULATIVE EFFECT</h4><div><p>Each individual biased decision might seem small. But over time, these small moments add up:</p><ul><li>A person who is consistently overlooked becomes disengaged</li><li>A team that always hires "similar" people loses innovation</li><li>An organisation where certain groups rarely reach leadership struggles to attract diverse talent</li></ul><p><b>This is why awareness matters.</b> Small changes in everyday decisions can create significant positive change over time.</p></div></div></div>

<div class="section-content-wrapper"><div class="text-content-render"><p><b>What can leaders do?</b></p><p>While we cannot eliminate our biases entirely, we can take steps to reduce their impact:</p><ul><li><b>Slow down</b> – Bias thrives when we make quick, automatic decisions. Taking time to reflect can help.</li><li><b>Use structured processes</b> – Consistent criteria for hiring, feedback, and promotions reduce the space for bias.</li><li><b>Seek diverse perspectives</b> – Involve others in decisions. Different viewpoints can spot blind spots.</li><li><b>Question your assumptions</b> – When you form a quick judgement, ask yourself: "What evidence do I have? Could I be wrong?"</li><li><b>Track patterns</b> – Look at who you hire, promote, give feedback to, and include. Are there patterns that suggest bias?</li></ul></div></div></div>
                        <div class="navigation-buttons">
