                    <div class="section" id="quiz">
                        <div class="section-header"><h3>BIAS RECOGNITION QUIZ</h3></div>
                        <div class="section-content"><div class="section-content-wrapper"><div class="key-definition-box"><h4>TEST YOUR UNDERSTANDING</h4><div><p>Read each workplace scenario below and decide whether bias is present. After each answer, you will receive feedback explaining the type of bias involved, why it matters, and one inclusive leadership action that could help.</p></div></div></div>

<div class="section-content-wrapper"><div class="quiz-container" id="bias-quiz">

<div class="quiz-question-wrapper" style="display: block;">
<p class="quiz-question-text">Scenario 1 of 5</p>
<div class="quiz-scenario">
<p><b>The Situation:</b></p>
<p>Sarah is reviewing CVs for a customer service role. She has two equally qualified candidates. She finds herself drawn to James's application because he went to the same university as her and lists "running" as a hobby – just like Sarah. She decides to invite James for an interview first.</p>
</div>
<p><b>Is bias present in this scenario?</b></p>
<div class="quiz-options">
<div class="quiz-option" data-value="A"><span>A</span><p>Yes, bias is present</p></div>
<div class="quiz-option" data-value="B"><span>B</span><p>No, this is fair decision-making</p></div>
</div>
<div class="quiz-feedback correct">
<h5>Correct! Bias is present.</h5>
<p class="bias-type">Type of bias: Affinity Bias</p>
<p class="why-matters">Why it matters: Sarah is unconsciously favouring a candidate because of personal similarities (same university, same hobby) rather than job-relevant criteria. This could mean equally or more qualified candidates are overlooked simply because they are "different" from the decision-maker.</p>
<div class="leadership-action"><strong>Inclusive Leadership Action:</strong> Use structured scoring criteria based solely on job requirements. Review CVs with names and personal details removed where possible, and have multiple people involved in shortlisting to balance individual biases.</div>
</div>
<div class="quiz-feedback incorrect">
<h5>Not quite. Bias IS present in this scenario.</h5>
<p class="bias-type">Type of bias: Affinity Bias</p>
<p class="why-matters">Why it matters: Sarah is unconsciously favouring a candidate because of personal similarities (same university, same hobby) rather than job-relevant criteria. While this feels natural, it means qualified candidates who are "different" from us get overlooked.</p>
<div class="leadership-action"><strong>Inclusive Leadership Action:</strong> Use structured scoring criteria based solely on job requirements. Review CVs with names and personal details removed where possible, and have multiple people involved in shortlisting to balance individual biases.</div>
</div>
<div class="quiz-nav">
<button class="quiz-check-btn" onclick="checkBiasQuiz(this, 'A')">Check Answer</button>
<button class="quiz-next-btn" onclick="nextBiasQuestion(this)">Next Question</button>
</div>
</div>

<div class="quiz-question-wrapper" style="display: none;">
<p class="quiz-question-text">Scenario 2 of 5</p>
<div class="quiz-scenario">
<p><b>The Situation:</b></p>
<p>During a team meeting, Priya suggests a new approach to handling customer complaints. The idea does not get much response. Ten minutes later, David makes essentially the same suggestion, and the manager says, "Great idea, David! Let's explore that."</p>
</div>
<p><b>Is bias present in this scenario?</b></p>
<div class="quiz-options">
<div class="quiz-option" data-value="A"><span>A</span><p>Yes, bias is present</p></div>
<div class="quiz-option" data-value="B"><span>B</span><p>No, this is fair decision-making</p></div>
</div>
<div class="quiz-feedback correct">
<h5>Correct! Bias is present.</h5>
<p class="bias-type">Type of bias: Gender Bias (and/or Affinity Bias)</p>
<p class="why-matters">Why it matters: The same idea is valued differently depending on who says it. This is a common pattern where contributions from women or minority group members are overlooked, while the same ideas from others are praised. Over time, this erodes confidence and engagement.</p>
<div class="leadership-action"><strong>Inclusive Leadership Action:</strong> Actively track who contributes ideas and ensure credit goes to the original source. Say things like "I think Priya mentioned something similar earlier – Priya, could you expand on your idea?" Make space for all voices to be heard.</div>
</div>
<div class="quiz-feedback incorrect">
<h5>Not quite. Bias IS present in this scenario.</h5>
<p class="bias-type">Type of bias: Gender Bias (and/or Affinity Bias)</p>
<p class="why-matters">Why it matters: The same idea is valued differently depending on who says it. While it might seem accidental, this pattern is common and can significantly impact who feels heard and valued in a team.</p>
<div class="leadership-action"><strong>Inclusive Leadership Action:</strong> Actively track who contributes ideas and ensure credit goes to the original source. Say things like "I think Priya mentioned something similar earlier – Priya, could you expand on your idea?" Make space for all voices to be heard.</div>
</div>
<div class="quiz-nav">
<button class="quiz-check-btn" onclick="checkBiasQuiz(this, 'A')">Check Answer</button>
<button class="quiz-next-btn" onclick="nextBiasQuestion(this)">Next Question</button>
</div>
</div>

<div class="quiz-question-wrapper" style="display: none;">
<p class="quiz-question-text">Scenario 3 of 5</p>
<div class="quiz-scenario">
<p><b>The Situation:</b></p>
<p>Tom, aged 58, has worked in the company for 20 years. A new digital transformation project is starting, and the manager is selecting the team. Tom is not considered because the manager assumes "he probably wouldn't be comfortable with all the new technology" – without actually asking Tom about his interest or skills.</p>
</div>
<p><b>Is bias present in this scenario?</b></p>
<div class="quiz-options">
<div class="quiz-option" data-value="A"><span>A</span><p>Yes, bias is present</p></div>
<div class="quiz-option" data-value="B"><span>B</span><p>No, this is fair decision-making</p></div>
</div>
<div class="quiz-feedback correct">
<h5>Correct! Bias is present.</h5>
<p class="bias-type">Type of bias: Age Bias (Ageism)</p>
<p class="why-matters">Why it matters: The manager made an assumption about Tom's capabilities based purely on his age, without any evidence. Tom might be highly skilled with technology, or eager to learn. Age-based assumptions deny people opportunities and waste valuable experience and talent.</p>
<div class="leadership-action"><strong>Inclusive Leadership Action:</strong> Never assume someone's interest or capability based on age. Advertise opportunities to everyone and let people self-select. Have honest conversations about development interests rather than making assumptions.</div>
</div>
<div class="quiz-feedback incorrect">
<h5>Not quite. Bias IS present in this scenario.</h5>
<p class="bias-type">Type of bias: Age Bias (Ageism)</p>
<p class="why-matters">Why it matters: Assumptions were made about Tom's capabilities without any evidence – just based on his age. This is a classic example of age bias that denies people opportunities.</p>
<div class="leadership-action"><strong>Inclusive Leadership Action:</strong> Never assume someone's interest or capability based on age. Advertise opportunities to everyone and let people self-select. Have honest conversations about development interests rather than making assumptions.</div>
</div>
<div class="quiz-nav">
<button class="quiz-check-btn" onclick="checkBiasQuiz(this, 'A')">Check Answer</button>
<button class="quiz-next-btn" onclick="nextBiasQuestion(this)">Next Question</button>
</div>
</div>

<div class="quiz-question-wrapper" style="display: none;">
<p class="quiz-question-text">Scenario 4 of 5</p>
<div class="quiz-scenario">
<p><b>The Situation:</b></p>
<p>Emma gave an outstanding presentation to the senior leadership team last month. Since then, her manager has rated her highly in all areas of her performance review, including areas where she has previously struggled (like time management and attention to detail). When a colleague points this out, the manager says, "She's clearly got what it takes – she'll figure those things out."</p>
</div>
<p><b>Is bias present in this scenario?</b></p>
<div class="quiz-options">
<div class="quiz-option" data-value="A"><span>A</span><p>Yes, bias is present</p></div>
<div class="quiz-option" data-value="B"><span>B</span><p>No, this is fair decision-making</p></div>
</div>
<div class="quiz-feedback correct">
<h5>Correct! Bias is present.</h5>
<p class="bias-type">Type of bias: The Halo Effect</p>
<p class="why-matters">Why it matters: One impressive achievement has created a "halo" that is colouring the manager's view of Emma's entire performance. While positive for Emma in the short term, this means she is not getting accurate feedback on genuine development areas – which could hold her back in the long run. It also creates unfairness for other team members who are judged more objectively.</p>
<div class="leadership-action"><strong>Inclusive Leadership Action:</strong> Use specific evidence for each competency area in performance reviews. Rate each area independently rather than letting one strength (or weakness) influence everything. Ask: "What specific evidence do I have for THIS rating?"</div>
</div>
<div class="quiz-feedback incorrect">
<h5>Not quite. Bias IS present in this scenario.</h5>
<p class="bias-type">Type of bias: The Halo Effect</p>
<p class="why-matters">Why it matters: One success is unfairly influencing judgements about completely separate performance areas. This prevents accurate feedback and creates unfairness across the team.</p>
<div class="leadership-action"><strong>Inclusive Leadership Action:</strong> Use specific evidence for each competency area in performance reviews. Rate each area independently rather than letting one strength (or weakness) influence everything. Ask: "What specific evidence do I have for THIS rating?"</div>
</div>
<div class="quiz-nav">
<button class="quiz-check-btn" onclick="checkBiasQuiz(this, 'A')">Check Answer</button>
<button class="quiz-next-btn" onclick="nextBiasQuestion(this)">Next Question</button>
</div>
</div>

<div class="quiz-question-wrapper" style="display: none;">
<p class="quiz-question-text">Scenario 5 of 5</p>
<div class="quiz-scenario">
<p><b>The Situation:</b></p>
<p>Marcus had a difficult start when he joined the team – he made some mistakes in his first month. Six months later, Marcus has improved significantly and consistently delivers good work. However, his manager still sees him as "the one who struggles" and continues to assign him only simple tasks. When Marcus asks for more challenging work, his manager hesitates, remembering those early mistakes.</p>
</div>
<p><b>Is bias present in this scenario?</b></p>
<div class="quiz-options">
<div class="quiz-option" data-value="A"><span>A</span><p>Yes, bias is present</p></div>
<div class="quiz-option" data-value="B"><span>B</span><p>No, this is fair decision-making</p></div>
</div>
<div class="quiz-feedback correct">
<h5>Correct! Bias is present.</h5>
<p class="bias-type">Type of bias: Confirmation Bias</p>
<p class="why-matters">Why it matters: The manager formed an early opinion of Marcus and continues to see him through that lens – focusing on evidence that confirms the original view (early mistakes) while ignoring evidence that contradicts it (six months of good work). This traps Marcus in an unfair perception and limits his growth.</p>
<div class="leadership-action"><strong>Inclusive Leadership Action:</strong> Regularly review and update your assessments of team members based on recent performance, not old impressions. Actively look for evidence that might contradict your existing views. Ask yourself: "Am I judging this person based on who they are NOW, or who they were?"</div>
</div>
<div class="quiz-feedback incorrect">
<h5>Not quite. Bias IS present in this scenario.</h5>
<p class="bias-type">Type of bias: Confirmation Bias</p>
<p class="why-matters">Why it matters: The manager is stuck on an old impression and ignoring six months of evidence that Marcus has improved. This is confirmation bias – only seeing what confirms our existing beliefs.</p>
<div class="leadership-action"><strong>Inclusive Leadership Action:</strong> Regularly review and update your assessments of team members based on recent performance, not old impressions. Actively look for evidence that might contradict your existing views. Ask yourself: "Am I judging this person based on who they are NOW, or who they were?"</div>
</div>
<div class="quiz-nav">
<button class="quiz-check-btn" onclick="checkBiasQuiz(this, 'A')">Check Answer</button>
<button class="quiz-next-btn" onclick="nextBiasQuestion(this)">Next Question</button>
</div>
</div>

